docs.abstract: “The way you saw my brother tortured and murdered on camera is the way black people are treated by police in America,” Philonise Floyd told diplomats.
docs.snippet: “The way you saw my brother tortured and murdered on camera is the way black people are treated by police in America,” Philonise Floyd told diplomats.
docs.lead_paragraph: GENEVA — The brother of George Floyd implored the United Nations on Wednesday to mount an investigation into racism, police brutality and police killings of unarmed black people in the United States.

headline.main: George Floyd’s Brother Urges U.N. to Investigate Police Killings in U.S.
headline.print_headline: U.N. Weighs An Inquiry On Racism In the U.S.

keywords.value: Human Rights and Human Rights Violations

docs.abstract: Gundy’s players threatened a boycott when he wore a shirt promoting One America News Network.
docs.snippet: Gundy’s players threatened a boycott when he wore a shirt promoting One America News Network.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mike Gundy, the winningest football coach in Oklahoma State’s history, apologized on Tuesday after he stirred outrage by wearing a T-shirt with the logo of a right-wing cable channel that aired commentary calling the Black Lives Matter movement “a farce.”

headline.main: Oklahoma State’s Gundy Apologizes for Wearing Shirt of Right-Wing Channel
headline.print_headline: Oklahoma State Coach Gives Apology for Right-Wing Shirt

docs.abstract: On Saturday, the artist Jammie Holmes staged his own kind of protest in five cities across the country.
docs.snippet: On Saturday, the artist Jammie Holmes staged his own kind of protest in five cities across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: Just after 12:30 p.m. on Saturday, as cooped-up New Yorkers spilled onto the Battery Park City esplanade — most in groups of two or three, each stationed a safe distance apart — a small plane glided past the Statue of Liberty and into view over the Hudson River. A banner swelled behind it, which read, “They’re Going to Kill Me.” These were among the last words of George Floyd, a black man who was killed while in the custody of the Minneapolis Police Department on May 25, and whose death has spurred demonstrations all over the country.

headline.main: George Floyd’s Final Words, Written in the Sky

docs.abstract: The Africa Center posted the Black Lives Matter sign as cultural organizations across the city offered programming in the spirit of the holiday.
docs.snippet: The Africa Center posted the Black Lives Matter sign as cultural organizations across the city offered programming in the spirit of the holiday.
docs.lead_paragraph: Six-foot letters filled 16 windows of the Africa Center on Friday as the side of the center’s home, a Robert A.M. Stern-designed building in Harlem, became a canvas that spelled out “Black Lives Matter.”

headline.main: A Sign, Rising 45 Feet, Heralds the Juneteenth Holiday in New York

docs.abstract: U.S. protests, coronavirus, global recession: What you need to know.
docs.snippet: U.S. protests, coronavirus, global recession: What you need to know.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two weeks after George Floyd’s death in Minneapolis police custody, the protests for racial justice around the United States, and now in other countries, have achieved a scale and momentum not seen in decades. And they seem unlikely to stop anytime soon.

docs.abstract: Some demonstrators, and in some cases the police, have paused to kneel, recalling the manner of George Floyd’s death and the gesture by Colin Kaepernick.
docs.snippet: Some demonstrators, and in some cases the police, have paused to kneel, recalling the manner of George Floyd’s death and the gesture by Colin Kaepernick.
docs.lead_paragraph: It is a simple gesture, swaddled in outrage and long-endured grief, that gained powerful currency through the protest against police brutality and racial injustice led by quarterback Colin Kaepernick on the fields of the National Football League.

headline.main: Kneeling, Fiercely Debated in the N.F.L., Resonates in Protests
headline.print_headline: Taking a Knee: From Sidelines To Front Lines

docs.abstract: For teens and young adults who join demonstrations, experts suggest measures that can reduce the potential for harm.
docs.snippet: For teens and young adults who join demonstrations, experts suggest measures that can reduce the potential for harm.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Sandy Asirvatham’s 17-year-old son, Miles Donovan, expressed interest in attending a protest this week near their downtown Baltimore home, she appreciated that he wanted to demonstrate solidarity with those who are outraged over the death of George Floyd. But just hours before it started, she began to worry.

headline.main: Have a Teenager Joining a Protest? Talk About Safety First
headline.print_headline: Here to Help; Have a Teenager Joining a Protest? Talk About Safety

docs.abstract: A playwright, a director, an artistic director and an actor share their experiences — and prescriptions for change.
docs.snippet: A playwright, a director, an artistic director and an actor share their experiences — and prescriptions for change.
docs.lead_paragraph: What has been the impact of race, and racism, on African-Americans working in the theater world? How should that world change? Those questions have taken on renewed, impassioned life since the killing of George Floyd, the shooting deaths of Ahmaud Arbery and Breonna Taylor, and the nationwide protests over racial injustice that have followed.

headline.main: Four Black Artists on How Racism Corrodes the Theater World

byline.original: By Laura Collins-Hughes, Michael Paulson and Salamishah Tillet

docs.abstract: A Georgia investigator testified that one of the three defendants accused of chasing down and killing Ahmaud Arbery heard another defendant use a racist slur.
docs.snippet: A Georgia investigator testified that one of the three defendants accused of chasing down and killing Ahmaud Arbery heard another defendant use a racist slur.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — A Georgia investigator testified on Thursday that one of the three white defendants accused of chasing down and killing Ahmaud Arbery, a black man who was running in a South Georgia neighborhood, heard another defendant use a racist slur moments after firing the shotgun blasts that ended Mr. Arbery’s life.

headline.main: Judge Finds Probable Cause for Murder Charges in Arbery Case
headline.print_headline: Testimony of Racist Slur Escalates Arbery Case

docs.abstract: The latest on stock market and business news during the coronavirus outbreak.
docs.snippet: The latest on stock market and business news during the coronavirus outbreak.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks on Tuesday mostly shrugged off increasingly chaotic scenes throughout the United States, as protesters and the police faced off across the country and President Trump threatened to use the military to quell widespread unrest precipitated by the death of George Floyd, a black man in Minneapolis, at the hands of the police last week.

headline.main: Stocks Rise as Investors Shrug Off Unrest
